{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17640868","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17640868"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:19:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:19:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17843"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17843","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17843"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10557"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78244"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10557","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10557"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17843"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63653"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10059"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24615"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24619"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26831"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78244","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78244"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine check-up. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She is interested in understanding more about how her body uses glucose, particularly which organs rely on glucose uptake even when she is fasting.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following pairs of organs is most reliant on constitutive glucose uptake?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Heart and liver","Brain and liver","Heart and kidney","Brain and kidney","Liver and kidney"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ebrain and kidney\u003C/strong\u003E are the organs most reliant on constitutive glucose uptake. The brain requires a continuous supply of glucose as it is its primary energy source, even during fasting states. The kidneys also need glucose for energy to perform essential functions such as filtration and reabsorption.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eheart\u003C/strong\u003E primarily uses fatty acids as its energy source, although it can use glucose, especially under conditions of increased demand or limited oxygen supply.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eliver\u003C/strong\u003E plays a central role in glucose metabolism, including gluconeogenesis and glycogen storage, but it does not rely on constitutive glucose uptake to the same extent as the brain and kidneys.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Constitutive glucose uptake is essential for organs that require a constant energy supply, such as the brain and kidneys.","The brain relies heavily on glucose as its primary energy source, even during fasting states.","The kidneys require glucose for energy to perform functions such as filtration and reabsorption."],"references":["Bender, D. A., \u0026 Cunningham, S. M. (2021). Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. CRC Press","Salway, J. G. (2016). Metabolism at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Chandel NS. Carbohydrate Metabolism. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Biol. 2021 Jan 4;13(1):a040568. doi: 10.1101/cshperspect.a040568. PMID: 33397651; PMCID: PMC7778149"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63653"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17843"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.co